definitions.definition: ( transitive ) To close with a hatch or hatches.

main_definition: ( transitive ) To close with a hatch or hatches.

definitions.definition: ( intransitive , of young animals ) To emerge from an egg .
examples: These three chicks hatched yesterday morning.

definitions.definition: ( intransitive , of eggs ) To break open when a young animal emerges from it.
examples: She was delighted when she heard the crackling sound of the eggs hatching .

definitions.definition: ( transitive ) To incubate eggs; to cause to hatch.
examples: I'm hatching this mysterious egg I found in the forest.

definitions.definition: ( transitive ) To devise (a plot or scheme ).
examples: World domination was only one of the evil schemes he had hatched over the years.

main_definition: ( intransitive , of young animals ) To emerge from an egg .
secondary_definitions: ( intransitive , of eggs ) To break open when a young animal emerges from it.
( transitive ) To incubate eggs; to cause to hatch.
( transitive ) To devise (a plot or scheme ).

definitions.definition: To shade an area of (a drawing, diagram, etc.) with fine parallel lines, or with lines which cross each other ( crosshatch ).
To cross; to spot; to stain; to steep.

main_definition: ( transitive ) To shade an area of (a drawing, diagram, etc.) with fine parallel lines, or with lines which cross each other ( crosshatch ).
secondary_definitions: ( transitive , obsolete ) To cross; to spot; to stain; to steep.
